01:49.540 --> 01:53.169
Lemond Bishop.
He's no longer a client.

01:53.210 --> 01:56.475
INTERVIEWER: To your knowledge,
has Lemond Bishop contributed

01:56.510 --> 01:59.217
to your campaign
or your PAC?

01:59.250 --> 02:00.239
No.

02:00.280 --> 02:02.145
MAN:
She's lying.

02:02.190 --> 02:04.545
How do you know?
Because she used
to represent Bishop.

02:04.590 --> 02:06.911
And you're giving her a
free ride this saint crap.

02:06.960 --> 02:09.485
Uh, M-Martin, I benefit just
as much as she does from...

02:09.530 --> 02:11.259
Frank, she got
the endorsement.

02:11.290 --> 02:13.155
She lied, and she got the
newspaper's endorsement.

02:13.200 --> 02:15.555
That's a three-point bump
three days before the election.

02:15.600 --> 02:18.626
So set up more events.
I'm here; I'm ready.

02:18.670 --> 02:20.535
Is this another
"Come to Jesus" moment?

02:20.570 --> 02:22.606
'Cause I don't know
how many more of these

02:22.640 --> 02:23.732
I can take, Martin.

02:23.770 --> 02:25.806
Look, I like you, Frank.

02:25.840 --> 02:28.274
You're a good man,
possibly even a great one,

02:28.310 --> 02:30.778
and I will do everything
I can to help you win...

02:30.810 --> 02:32.471
but you are too nice.

02:32.520 --> 02:34.408
She's a liar.
She told them...

02:34.450 --> 02:35.769
Exactly what they
wanted to hear,

02:35.820 --> 02:38.311
and I'll bet you
every dollar I have

02:38.350 --> 02:40.489
they knew she was lying,
they wanted her to lie--

02:40.520 --> 02:42.624
because people respect
someone who's willing

02:42.660 --> 02:45.322
to lie for what
they believe in.

02:45.360 --> 02:47.328
It shows strength.

02:47.360 --> 02:48.952
They don't respect
the truth.

02:49.000 --> 02:50.820
Every time you said something
self-deprecatingly true

02:50.870 --> 02:53.896
to that editorial board, they
all patted you on the back

02:53.940 --> 02:55.339
and then snickered
behind their hands.

02:55.370 --> 02:56.564
I won't smear her.

02:56.610 --> 02:58.601
That's always what
this comes down to.

02:58.640 --> 03:00.198
I won't go against
my principles.

03:00.240 --> 03:01.605
You disagree with her?

03:01.640 --> 03:02.800
Yes, on policy.

03:02.850 --> 03:04.249
You disagree with her husband?

03:04.280 --> 03:06.248
Yes.
There.

03:06.280 --> 03:07.269
Don't go after her;
go after him.

03:07.320 --> 03:08.548
I'm not running
against her husband.

03:08.580 --> 03:10.639
Exactly, so there's no problem
going after him.

03:10.690 --> 03:12.351
He was corrupt.

03:12.390 --> 03:13.652
What will going
after her husband do?

03:13.690 --> 03:15.419
It will show _what
you're against.

03:15.460 --> 03:16.688
Campaigns aren't just
about what you're for.

03:16.730 --> 03:18.721
They're about
what you're against.

03:18.760 --> 03:19.897
So go after the husband.

03:19.930 --> 03:22.569
JOSH:
For the, uh, uh...

03:22.600 --> 03:24.568
I'm not leaving you in a lurch;
will you stop saying that?
Blah, blah, or whatever.

03:24.600 --> 03:25.862
Please?
Oh, so the whole...
What's going on?

03:25.900 --> 03:27.436
Nothing.
We're...

03:27.470 --> 03:28.767
We've got a problem.

03:28.800 --> 03:31.701
MELISSA:
We can see that.
Tell her the problem, Jon.

03:31.740 --> 03:33.731
Okay.

03:33.780 --> 03:35.577
Uh, the first thing I'll do
is clean house

03:35.610 --> 03:36.872
and take a look at hiring

03:36.910 --> 03:39.242
going back to
Peter Florrick's administra--

03:39.280 --> 03:41.578
So our tracker just picked
this up outside the hotel.

03:41.620 --> 03:42.382
What's wrong with it?

03:42.420 --> 03:44.888
Peter Florrick
brought a new level

03:44.920 --> 03:46.717
of cronyism to the office,

03:46.760 --> 03:48.250
and that's what
I'll need to root out.

03:48.290 --> 03:49.780
Uh, the office needs
an upheaval,

03:49.830 --> 03:51.582
not the partial measures
of Mr. Florrick.

03:51.630 --> 03:53.894
Okay, so he mentions Peter
eight times

03:53.930 --> 03:55.750
in the space of whatever,
a short time.

03:55.800 --> 03:56.926
JOHNNY:
He's coming after you

03:56.970 --> 03:58.494
through your husband.
That's his way

03:58.530 --> 03:59.861
of getting around
your, you know,

03:59.900 --> 04:01.561
little thing.
Your agreement

04:01.600 --> 04:02.669
to not go negative.

04:02.710 --> 04:03.665
So, what do I do, defend Peter?

04:03.710 --> 04:04.699
No, that's exactly
what they want.

04:04.740 --> 04:06.298
I think the time has come

04:06.340 --> 04:07.602
for you to separate yourself.

04:07.640 --> 04:09.540
_ You need
your Sister soulja moment.

04:09.580 --> 04:11.673
So I should criticize Peter?

04:11.710 --> 04:13.746
Yes, his issues.
What issues?

04:13.780 --> 04:15.316
Doesn't matter;
pick one.
God, this is like high school.

04:15.350 --> 04:16.647
The key is to create
a little space

04:16.690 --> 04:17.816
between you and Peter.
That way,

04:17.850 --> 04:18.942
Prady can say whatever he wants,

04:18.990 --> 04:19.979
and none of it
Will land on you.

04:20.020 --> 04:21.317
And what's the con?

04:21.360 --> 04:22.384
The con?

04:22.430 --> 04:23.988
Why wouldn't I do this?

04:24.030 --> 04:25.429
The two of you
were arguing before.

04:25.460 --> 04:27.291
Who's against it?
No.

04:27.330 --> 04:29.366
No, that's not what
we were arguing about.

04:29.400 --> 04:30.469
Tell her,

04:30.500 --> 04:31.660
big man.

04:33.000 --> 04:35.491
(anxious laugh)
Uh...

04:35.540 --> 04:37.030
I've been asked to join
a campaign

04:37.070 --> 04:38.628
in Sacramento on the 7th.

04:38.670 --> 04:39.978
The 7th of...?
This month,

04:40.010 --> 04:41.409
Election Day,
but don't worry.

04:41.440 --> 04:42.600
You are in great shape.

04:42.650 --> 04:43.901
There's not really anything
to be done

04:43.950 --> 04:45.042
on the campaign
at that point.

04:45.080 --> 04:46.616
And this being Chicago,
you know,

04:46.650 --> 04:48.049
there's never any
fraud at the polls.

04:48.080 --> 04:49.411
(phone rings)
Come on, Josh. That's not fair.

04:49.450 --> 04:50.587
We've got lawyers for exactly

04:50.620 --> 04:52.588
that kind of thing.
Alicia...

04:52.620 --> 04:54.781
How's he doing on the stand?
What?

04:54.820 --> 04:57.653
McVeigh, how's he doing
on the stand?

04:57.690 --> 04:59.396
Oh, I don't know;
I haven't checked in.

04:59.430 --> 05:00.499
That's not why I'm calling.

05:00.530 --> 05:01.758
Louis Canning called you.

05:01.800 --> 05:04.360
What? Why?
Uh, he wants to see you.

05:04.400 --> 05:05.867
He's in ICU, but we think
it's a good idea.

05:05.900 --> 05:07.367
We? What do you mean?

05:07.400 --> 05:08.697
We think it's a good idea

05:08.740 --> 05:10.708
for you to go and see him
and get him to sign off

05:10.740 --> 05:11.764
on his lawsuit against us.

05:11.810 --> 05:13.505
While he's in the ICU?

05:13.540 --> 05:15.701
Yes.
You want me to pull an Ashcroft.

05:15.740 --> 05:18.072
Get him to sign something
when he's weak in the hospital?

05:18.110 --> 05:19.748
No, but you're going
to the hospital anyway,

05:19.780 --> 05:21.611
so it would be good for the firm

05:21.650 --> 05:23.083
if he accepted
our reasonable offer.

05:23.120 --> 05:24.519
Look, just call me
when you find out

05:24.550 --> 05:27.348
how McVeigh's doing
on the stand, okay?

05:27.390 --> 05:30.120
McVEIGH: The firearm was devised
through additive manufacturing,

05:30.160 --> 05:34.449
or as it's more popularly known,
3-D printing.

05:34.500 --> 05:35.421
And it works from software?

05:35.460 --> 05:36.597
Yes, open source file.

05:36.630 --> 05:38.461
So if I type in the words,

05:38.500 --> 05:40.639
uh, "3-D printer gun"

05:40.670 --> 05:43.434
right now, it would come up
with a file just like that?

05:43.470 --> 05:45.461
Yes, uh, Mr. Fife's design

05:45.510 --> 05:47.432
is still currently
on his Web site.

05:47.480 --> 05:48.879
POLMAR: So, once you've
downloaded all the schematics

05:48.910 --> 05:50.548
for the gun,

05:50.580 --> 05:52.411
how difficult is it
to print one?

05:52.450 --> 05:55.146
Load a spool of plastic
into a 3-D printer,

05:55.180 --> 05:57.080
push "print."
That's it?

05:57.120 --> 05:59.452
Yes, that's it.
Well, dear God,
that's appalling.

05:59.490 --> 06:00.752
I mean, how long
does it take to print?

06:00.790 --> 06:02.109
McVEIGH:
A gun, Your Honor?

06:02.160 --> 06:03.957
Approximately four hours.

06:03.990 --> 06:06.151
POLMAR:
So, on January the 17...

06:06.190 --> 06:08.727
And this gun, it fires
actual bullets?

06:08.760 --> 06:10.159
Yes, Your Honor.
And it's plastic,

06:10.200 --> 06:12.395
so you could get it through
a, uh, metal detector.

06:12.440 --> 06:13.862
Yes, Your Honor.
Whoof!

06:13.900 --> 06:15.993
Well, thank God for
the Second Amendment.

06:17.170 --> 06:20.003
Well, Your Honor,
this technology

06:20.040 --> 06:22.008
has more to do
with the First Amendment

06:22.040 --> 06:24.076
than the Second.
No, no.
Not if the software can kill.

06:24.110 --> 06:25.702
Yes, but it's not the
sobeare that's killing.

06:25.750 --> 06:27.968
Your Honor, if we could show
you what happened next?

06:28.020 --> 06:30.011
Yeah, yeah, of course.
My apologies.

06:30.050 --> 06:33.679
Um, and I promise
I won't let my bias

06:33.720 --> 06:35.017
impact my decision.
Thank you, Your Honor.

06:35.060 --> 06:37.153
You've always been very fair,

06:37.190 --> 06:38.748
so we're counting on that.
So,

06:38.790 --> 06:41.190
Mr. McVeigh, this is
the gun that was taken

06:41.230 --> 06:42.197
to the Cantata Vega
Shooting Range?

06:42.230 --> 06:43.663
Is that correct?
Yes.

06:43.700 --> 06:46.021
And what happened
at that range?

06:46.070 --> 06:47.731
The gun misfired

06:47.770 --> 06:50.762
and sent shrapnel
through an alley partition

06:50.810 --> 06:52.209
and injured the spine
of Mr. Summerfeldt.

06:52.240 --> 06:53.502
So the misfire

06:53.540 --> 06:55.576
that paralyzed my client
was foreseeable?

06:55.610 --> 06:56.747
Yes, by someone

06:56.780 --> 06:58.668
with experience in printing

06:58.710 --> 07:01.213
and testing 3-D printed guns.

07:01.250 --> 07:03.218
And the shooter, Carsten Pope,
did he have that experience?

07:03.250 --> 07:04.740
McVEIGH:
No, he had never printed

07:04.790 --> 07:06.655
nor fired a gun
like that before.

07:06.690 --> 07:07.816
So who should've known?

07:07.860 --> 07:09.521
The gun designer, Mr. Fife.

07:09.560 --> 07:11.687
He is the expert here;
he made the gun

07:11.730 --> 07:14.927
readily available to the public.
The responsibility is his.

07:14.960 --> 07:17.793
Thank you, Mr. McVeigh.
Nothing further, Your Honor.

07:17.830 --> 07:19.798
He's a good witness.

07:19.840 --> 07:22.502
Mr. McVeigh, how are you?
I'm good, thank you.

07:22.540 --> 07:24.462
Good. Thank you very much

07:24.510 --> 07:26.637
for taking us all
through this technology.

07:26.680 --> 07:28.705
It just seems to get
more and more complicated,

07:28.740 --> 07:30.674
doesn't it?
Oh, yeah, it does.

07:30.710 --> 07:33.975
And culpability, then,
gets more and more complicated,

07:34.020 --> 07:35.817
because it goes through
so many different hands.

07:35.850 --> 07:37.579
Objection, Your Honor.

07:37.620 --> 07:39.588
Ms. Crozier seems to be confused

07:39.620 --> 07:40.780
as to who is on
the witness stand.

07:40.820 --> 07:42.526
No. (chuckles)

07:42.560 --> 07:44.528
I'm just plain confused.

07:44.560 --> 07:46.050
It's not like there's
one manufacturer and one...

07:46.090 --> 07:48.149
Your Honor?
Yeah, um...

07:48.200 --> 07:49.827
Sustained. Is anybody else

07:49.870 --> 07:53.135
really disturbed by all this?

07:53.170 --> 07:54.967
(all talking at once)

07:55.000 --> 07:55.989
Okay, okay, thank you.

07:56.040 --> 07:57.268
That was rhetorical.

07:57.310 --> 07:59.631
Um, no more
editorial content from me.

07:59.680 --> 08:01.705
Ms. Crozier?
Thank you, Your Honor.

08:01.740 --> 08:04.277
So, Mr. McVeigh,

08:04.310 --> 08:05.971
The shooter, Mr. Pope,

08:06.010 --> 08:07.944
sitting right there,
you're not suing him,

08:07.980 --> 08:10.915
Right?
Actually, I'm not suing anyone,
Ms. Crozier.

08:10.950 --> 08:13.510
You're just an expert witness

08:13.560 --> 08:15.255
who happens to be married

08:15.290 --> 08:17.656
_to_one of
the plaintiff's attorneys.

08:17.690 --> 08:19.055
Sorry, let me rephrase that.

08:19.090 --> 08:20.955
The shooter, Mr. Pope,

08:21.000 --> 08:22.968
the one that your wife
is not suing,

08:23.000 --> 08:24.092
he built the gun

08:24.130 --> 08:25.620
that injured
Eddie Summerfeldt.

08:25.670 --> 08:26.989
No.

08:27.040 --> 08:28.632
No.No?

08:28.670 --> 08:29.807
He didn't?
He didn't build it.

08:29.840 --> 08:31.137
He printed it.
But you said that

08:31.170 --> 08:33.309
he didn't have any training
in 3-D printing.

08:33.340 --> 08:35.001
That's correct.
Do you know where he made...

08:35.040 --> 08:37.577
or printed, the gun?

08:37.610 --> 08:38.747
In his garage.

08:38.780 --> 08:40.077
And he spent $25?

08:40.120 --> 08:41.144
God help us.
$22.50

08:41.180 --> 08:43.284
in materials,

08:43.320 --> 08:45.618
and $1,795

08:45.650 --> 08:46.287
for the printer.

08:46.320 --> 08:47.582
Well, I mean,

08:47.620 --> 08:49.622
I don't know much about guns.

08:49.660 --> 08:50.820
You're the expert there,

08:50.860 --> 08:52.623
but I'm still just trying

08:52.660 --> 08:54.150
to figure out why it is

08:54.200 --> 08:55.827
you're suing my client,

08:55.860 --> 08:58.988
who's merely responsible
for the design of the thing,

08:59.030 --> 09:01.931
and not the shooter,
who actually printed

09:01.970 --> 09:03.335
and fired the gun.

09:03.370 --> 09:05.930
Again, ma'am,
I'm not suing anyone.

09:05.970 --> 09:07.870
Well, maybe you could
just convince your wife...

09:07.910 --> 09:09.002
Objection, Your Honor.

09:09.040 --> 09:10.348
I'll sustain that.

09:10.380 --> 09:12.075
I just, H,
I just can't believe it.

09:12.110 --> 09:14.908
Twenty-five dollars.

09:31.330 --> 09:34.731
How is it that you make
me feel like I'm 22?

09:42.280 --> 09:45.340
* Whoo!

09:51.690 --> 09:53.317
How are you, Mr. Canning?

09:53.360 --> 09:54.952
I'm alive.

09:54.990 --> 09:56.252
But you got a new kidney.

09:56.290 --> 09:57.621
Yes.

09:57.660 --> 09:59.651
Sit, sit there.

10:02.700 --> 10:04.224
So, were you elected?

10:04.270 --> 10:05.396
(chuckles) No.

10:05.430 --> 10:07.990
Oh, you lost.

10:08.040 --> 10:09.962
No, it's just three days away.

10:10.010 --> 10:12.069
Oh.

10:12.110 --> 10:13.236
I voted absentee.

10:13.280 --> 10:14.406
Thank you.

10:14.440 --> 10:16.101
No, against you.

10:16.140 --> 10:17.368
(chuckles)

10:24.020 --> 10:25.681
So, Mr. Canning,
if you don't mind...

10:25.720 --> 10:27.381
This girl,
this 13-year-old girl,

10:27.420 --> 10:31.322
went to head a soccer ball
at her junior league game,

10:31.360 --> 10:33.920
and, uh, her head

10:33.960 --> 10:36.690
hit another girl's head,

10:36.730 --> 10:38.425
and she died.

10:38.470 --> 10:40.859
She just...

10:40.900 --> 10:43.437
dropped to the field, dead.

10:43.470 --> 10:45.665
And I don't even know her name.

10:48.140 --> 10:50.005
But she gave me a kidney.

10:50.050 --> 10:52.405
Can you believe that?

10:52.450 --> 10:54.270
I can.

10:54.320 --> 10:58.711
So, I swore to myself
before I went into surgery

10:58.750 --> 11:01.184
that I'd do something for her.

11:01.220 --> 11:05.782
If it worked out,
if-if it went well,

11:05.830 --> 11:07.923
and I lived
that I would do something good.

11:07.960 --> 11:11.066
For her family?
Yes.

11:11.100 --> 11:13.239
I want to liquidate my stocks.

11:13.270 --> 11:15.090
$18 million.

11:15.140 --> 11:17.802
Give them to her family.

11:17.840 --> 11:19.774
Will you do that for me?

11:21.980 --> 11:23.800
Have you called
your estate lavwer?

11:23.850 --> 11:25.477
Yes, he's not
returning my calls.

11:25.510 --> 11:28.047
Think he wants to wait
till I'm dead, and then...

11:28.080 --> 11:30.082
keep all the money in-house.

11:34.020 --> 11:36.318
Who is your estate attorney?

11:36.360 --> 11:39.227
David Lee.

11:39.260 --> 11:42.821
(groans quietly)

11:58.810 --> 12:00.141
FIFE:
I didn't put the file up
to hurt people.

12:00.180 --> 12:02.011
I put it up to protect them.

12:02.050 --> 12:05.781
That you'll have to explain,
Mr. Fife. You wanted to

12:05.820 --> 12:08.857
protect my client
by providing schematics for guns

12:08.890 --> 12:10.255
that are undetectable,

12:10.290 --> 12:11.928
untraceable and unregulated?

12:11.960 --> 12:13.496
Yeah, and uncensorable.

12:13.530 --> 12:15.418
So, this is all about the
First Amendment to you?

12:15.460 --> 12:17.121
Yes. Yes, Your Honor.

12:17.170 --> 12:18.762
