I do. I'm worried about
you losmg more votes

23:49.890 --> 23:52.222
than you'd gain... old-time
supporters of his, Christians.

23:52.260 --> 23:54.228
We've hitched our wagon
to Peter from the beginning.

23:54.260 --> 23:56.854
I'm worried that we might end
up looking like opportunists.

23:56.900 --> 23:59.789
But what about countering
Prady's attack?

23:59.830 --> 24:01.866
I looked at the overnights--
the attack doesn't seem

24:01.900 --> 24:03.037
to leave much of a mark.

24:03.070 --> 24:04.867
I'm thinking we play
to our base.

24:04.910 --> 24:06.866
You sure?
Yes.

24:06.910 --> 24:09.936
For better or for worse,
you guys are a brand.

24:09.980 --> 24:11.868
You're the Florricks.
A package deal.

24:11.910 --> 24:14.014
This is the first speech.
It'll be on the teleprompters.

24:16.220 --> 24:17.812
Okay.

24:17.850 --> 24:20.683
Okay. I'll see you at 1:00.

24:20.720 --> 24:24.724
Why are you leaving
Election Day?

24:26.730 --> 24:29.528
This job in Sacramento.
It's a special election.

24:29.560 --> 24:32.063
They... they're in trouble.

24:32.100 --> 24:33.931
So it's not because of me.
Of us.

24:33.970 --> 24:35.164
No.

24:35.200 --> 24:37.998
Okay.
Okay.

24:42.040 --> 24:44.179
What's this?

24:44.210 --> 24:46.644
I don't know.
It's too far away.

24:46.680 --> 24:47.874
What is it?
You amended the suit.

24:47.920 --> 24:50.980
Oh, yes, we did.
Based on your test.

24:51.020 --> 24:52.988
We're suing the maker
of the printer.
But you're still suing

24:53.020 --> 24:55.079
Chris Fife, even though his
design isn't the problem.

24:55.120 --> 24:58.283
Fife's Web site links
to the faulty printer.

24:58.330 --> 25:01.197
He specifically advocates
its use, so we're able

25:01.230 --> 25:04.199
to backdoor him.
You don't believe that
he is legally negligent.

25:04.230 --> 25:06.118
You just think he's
politically offensive.

25:06.170 --> 25:07.660
I think he's both.

25:07.700 --> 25:09.292
He's making it possible
for anyone to make

25:09.340 --> 25:11.729
an untraceable,
untrackable gun.

25:11.770 --> 25:14.204
Who do you think will use it?
That's not a question
for lawyers.

25:14.240 --> 25:16.936
That's for politicians.
You want to run? Run.

25:18.880 --> 25:20.302
We need you to testify, Kurt.

25:20.350 --> 25:23.114
I need you
to testify.
No.

25:23.150 --> 25:26.017
Not for a crusade.

25:29.860 --> 25:31.953
You can talk to him.

25:31.990 --> 25:33.594
Oh, that's all right.

25:33.630 --> 25:35.120
It helps.

25:35.160 --> 25:37.799
Squeeze his hand
and talk to him.

25:43.240 --> 25:45.606
Hi.

25:57.890 --> 25:59.881
So...

26:04.260 --> 26:06.057
I'm here because I need to know

26:06.090 --> 26:08.752
what you want me to do
with your money, Mr. Canning.

26:08.800 --> 26:12.998
This family, they want to give
it to a Palestinian charity,

26:13.030 --> 26:16.033
but it might have
illegal ties...

26:17.040 --> 26:20.259
(chuckles)

26:20.310 --> 26:25.338
She probably means talk
about something personal.

26:25.380 --> 26:29.248
My daughter's praying for you,
so that's good.

26:29.280 --> 26:32.989
I'm not. Because that
would be hypocritical.

26:43.200 --> 26:47.022
I don't want you to die,
Mr. Canning, okay?

26:48.140 --> 26:51.860
I know you're a bad man, but...

26:51.910 --> 26:54.208
(chuckles)

26:55.380 --> 26:58.770
...I sort of miss you.

26:59.780 --> 27:01.748
I know. That's weird.

27:01.780 --> 27:03.782
I don't know why.

27:06.220 --> 27:09.712
I seem to have some...

27:09.760 --> 27:11.728
bad boy issues.

27:11.760 --> 27:14.627
(wry laugh)

27:21.270 --> 27:24.398
Get well, Mr. Canning.

27:37.180 --> 27:38.386
Okay.

27:38.420 --> 27:41.685
I am gonna get your money
to that charity.

27:47.030 --> 27:49.328
Bye.

27:54.100 --> 27:56.364
(low, indistinct chatter,
footsteps approaching)

27:57.970 --> 28:00.029
MARISSA:
You're a real dirtbag,

28:00.070 --> 28:01.879
you know that?
No, I didn't know that.

28:01.910 --> 28:03.229
You're letting
my dad bully you.

28:03.280 --> 28:04.838
Marissa, you don't know what
you're talking about.

28:04.880 --> 28:06.404
He threatened
to yank your next job

28:06.450 --> 28:08.839
unless you advised Alicia
to back down.

28:08.880 --> 28:10.313
Alicia and Peter are better off
standing together.

28:10.350 --> 28:12.079
They're a package deal.
Package deal.

28:12.120 --> 28:13.917
Yeah, I heard my dad say it
already, dirtbag.

28:13.960 --> 28:15.211
Well, then Marissa, why don't
you leave me alone, okay?

28:15.260 --> 28:17.012
Your job is to give her

28:17.060 --> 28:18.425
ChapStick and breath mints,
not bust my balls.

28:18.460 --> 28:21.725
God, handsome men are so weak.

28:33.540 --> 28:35.872
Kurt McVeigh?

28:35.910 --> 28:38.276
Yeah?
You've been served.

28:38.310 --> 28:39.402
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

28:39.450 --> 28:41.042
Who's it from?

28:41.080 --> 28:43.378
Diane Lockhart.

28:52.930 --> 28:55.148
So you used the same BlockStock
3-D printer to make your gun

28:55.200 --> 28:58.328
as Carsten Pope did?

29:06.170 --> 29:07.432
Yes.

29:10.080 --> 29:12.048
And would you characterize it

29:12.080 --> 29:14.048
as a smooth process?

29:16.880 --> 29:19.747
I have nothing to compare it to.

29:22.020 --> 29:23.510
(chuckles)

29:23.560 --> 29:25.152
I think your, uh,

29:25.190 --> 29:27.488
witness would appreciate
some specificity.

29:27.530 --> 29:29.191
Let me rephrase.

29:29.230 --> 29:33.291
Did you find that when
you were making the gun...

29:33.330 --> 29:35.195
the printer stuttered?

29:36.240 --> 29:38.003
Yes.

29:38.040 --> 29:39.359
Were you able to determine why?

29:39.410 --> 29:44.803
There was too much friction
in the feed tube.

29:48.220 --> 29:51.144
And what effect _did this have
on the resulting print?
It prevented

29:51.190 --> 29:53.909
the layers of plastic
from being applied evenly.

29:53.960 --> 29:56.155
So when you test-fired the gun,
what happened?

29:56.190 --> 29:57.509
It misfired.
So would you say

29:57.560 --> 29:59.152
that the fault for this lies

29:59.190 --> 30:02.091
with BlockStock, the designer
of the 3-D printer?

30:03.260 --> 30:05.194
Yes.

30:05.230 --> 30:09.394
Your Honor, no offense to my
codefendants, but I fail to see

30:09.440 --> 30:11.908
how Mr. McVeigh's testimony
is relevant to my client.

30:11.940 --> 30:13.567
Uh, Ms. Lockhart,
would you care to enlighten us?

30:13.610 --> 30:16.238
Mr. Fife's Web site links
to the BlockStock

30:16.280 --> 30:17.907
3-D printer site.
Your Honor,

30:17.950 --> 30:20.168
_ _that connection
is ridiculously tenuous.

30:20.210 --> 30:22.144
POLMAR: It's joint and
several liability,

30:22.180 --> 30:23.545
Your Honor.

30:23.580 --> 30:26.048
Mr. Fife and BlockStock
were both negligent here.

30:26.090 --> 30:28.411
Therefore we can and should be
able to recover damages

30:28.460 --> 30:30.985
from both.
Makes sense to me.

30:31.030 --> 30:33.351
Mr. Fife should make himself
comfortable.

30:47.940 --> 30:50.909
So don't you want Diane here
and not me?

30:50.950 --> 30:53.271
No.

30:53.310 --> 30:56.143
This is the feed tube from
Carsten Pope's printer.

30:56.180 --> 30:59.081
Look through it.
Sure.

30:59.120 --> 31:01.111
I can't.
It's clogged.

31:01.160 --> 31:03.014
After Carsten Pope
printed his gun,

31:03.060 --> 31:05.187
he made several
coffee mugs.

31:05.230 --> 31:07.892
Okay, well,
that's oddly innocuous.

31:07.930 --> 31:10.319
You think that's what
caused the misfire,
mixing the plastics?

31:10.360 --> 31:12.328
I don't know.
That's why we test.

31:16.370 --> 31:18.338
Well, it's intact.

31:18.370 --> 31:20.235
So... that's bad?

31:20.270 --> 31:21.999
Maybe.

31:22.040 --> 31:23.632
Well, the printer
worked fine,

31:23.680 --> 31:25.238
which means that the company's
not at fault.

31:25.280 --> 31:27.248
Yeah, it also means
that the gun Pope fired

31:27.280 --> 31:29.111
wasn't based on a
bad design either.

31:29.150 --> 31:31.038
Right. Good.
Except, you know...
We have no idea

31:31.090 --> 31:33.388
why the gun failed.
Yeah.

31:33.420 --> 31:36.651
But the first order of
business is dropping BlockStock

31:36.690 --> 31:39.250
from the_ suit.
They did nothing wrong.

31:39.290 --> 31:41.656
Yeah.

31:41.700 --> 31:44.362
MAN:
BBL has always been about...

31:44.400 --> 31:46.664
WOMAN:
Do you want anything
for your hair?

31:46.700 --> 31:48.190
No. I'm good. Thank you.

31:48.240 --> 31:49.389
Okay.

31:52.740 --> 31:55.379
You think our campaign managers
know we're alone in here?

31:55.410 --> 31:58.208
I think our campaign
managers think

31:58.250 --> 31:59.603
we're running off together.
(chuckles)

31:59.650 --> 32:01.618
We could do worse.

32:01.650 --> 32:04.414
(phone ringing)

32:04.450 --> 32:07.044
Go ahead. I don't mind.
No.

32:07.090 --> 32:09.957
I'm sick of phones.
It's always bad news.

32:09.990 --> 32:11.423
Not for you these days.

32:11.460 --> 32:13.428
Not that I'm
following the polls.

32:13.460 --> 32:16.122
Oh, I think
it's too close to call.

32:16.160 --> 32:17.696
Oh, I don't think it is.

32:17.730 --> 32:19.698
Whenever I think
I'm certain about something,

32:19.730 --> 32:21.129
I'm always surprised.

32:21.170 --> 32:24.207
It's a bad process, isn't it?

32:24.240 --> 32:26.128
Horrible.

32:26.170 --> 32:29.708
Anything you'd do
differently?

32:30.710 --> 32:32.371
I'd be more honest.

32:34.250 --> 32:36.241
How 'bout you?

32:36.280 --> 32:38.145
The debate.

32:38.190 --> 32:39.441
Oh, right.
(chuckles)

32:39.490 --> 32:41.708
And the closeted charge.
I would answer it.

32:41.760 --> 32:43.250
You still can.

32:43.290 --> 32:45.178
No one thinks
it's wrong to be gay.

32:49.300 --> 32:52.098
Who else but your opponent?

32:53.230 --> 32:56.097
I'm not gay. I'm a Jesuit.

33:00.370 --> 33:02.179
because you only
get married once.

33:02.210 --> 33:05.646
To remarry is
to commit adultery.

33:05.680 --> 33:08.444
It's the God's
honest truth.

33:08.480 --> 33:10.744
Wh... Why didn't you say that?

33:10.780 --> 33:13.283
Well, we didn't
want to lose the gay vote

33:13.320 --> 33:17.154
and-and... besides,
it makes you look weird.

33:17.190 --> 33:19.488
What person in
this day and age

33:19.530 --> 33:21.725
takes Jesus
Christ seriously

33:21.760 --> 33:23.728
when he says,
"You can't divorce"?

33:23.760 --> 33:26.024
Not someone you
want to get a beer with.

33:30.300 --> 33:31.801
You are...

33:31.840 --> 33:33.728
better than I am.

33:33.770 --> 33:35.499
(chuckles):
No.

33:35.540 --> 33:37.303
Oh, yeah.

33:37.340 --> 33:39.774
Unfortunately.

33:41.220 --> 33:42.312
(soft knocking at door)

33:42.350 --> 33:44.147
Well...

33:48.220 --> 33:50.051
It's been good fighting you.

33:50.090 --> 33:51.523
Good luck on your speech.

33:51.560 --> 33:53.824
Think I should
put something in my hair?

33:53.860 --> 33:55.452
No.

33:55.500 --> 33:58.219
You're perfect.

34:21.190 --> 34:23.283
(line ringing)

34:23.320 --> 34:25.288
Hello, Eli, how are you?

34:25.330 --> 34:26.558
Well, that depends.
Are you sending money

34:26.590 --> 34:28.148
to the Palestinians?

34:31.430 --> 34:34.137
I hate these silences, Alicia.

34:34.170 --> 34:37.298
Where are you hearing this, Eli?
I just got a call from a friend
in the Justice Department.

34:37.340 --> 34:39.433
He asked me to check
if you're funding some...

34:39.470 --> 34:41.404
pro-Palestinian charity
based in Detroit.

34:41.440 --> 34:42.600
It's Dearborn.

34:42.640 --> 34:44.608
And no, I'm not.
Alicia, what the hell?

34:44.650 --> 34:47.505
You're sending money to Hamas?
No, it's not me,

34:47.550 --> 34:49.245
it's Louis Canning.
He's sick,

34:49.280 --> 34:50.440
and he wanted
to do something nice...

34:50.480 --> 34:52.812
What, send money to Hamas?
...for the

34:52.850 --> 34:54.454
donor of his kidney.

34:54.490 --> 34:58.529
They wanted to give money
to this charity, and...

34:58.560 --> 35:02.519
there's a possibility
that this charity...

35:02.560 --> 35:04.596
might be connected to Hamas.

35:04.630 --> 35:06.564
So I was checking on it
for him, that's all.

35:06.600 --> 35:08.693
Why were you checking?
Because he asked me to

35:08.740 --> 35:11.561
and David Lee wouldn't.
So I did.

35:12.770 --> 35:15.603
Oh, Alicia, you're being set up.

35:15.640 --> 35:16.709
What? What are you...

35:16.740 --> 35:18.605
This Canning guy
is suing you, right?

35:18.650 --> 35:20.675
And David Lee is no friend,
and they both found a way

35:20.710 --> 35:23.747
for you to check
on giving money to Hamas.
He's on his deathbed, Eli.

35:23.780 --> 35:27.341
Canning's not gonna
prank me on his deathbed.

35:27.390 --> 35:30.587
Why not?
Because...

35:30.620 --> 35:32.827
I don't know.
I'm giving up.

35:32.860 --> 35:35.249
Good-bye.

35:40.770 --> 35:42.533
What's wrong?

35:42.570 --> 35:45.437
Nothing.
What do you mean?

35:45.470 --> 35:47.529
You look like
something's wrong.

35:47.570 --> 35:49.731
No, but there's been a change.
You look great.

35:49.780 --> 35:51.702
Thanks. What changed?

35:51.750 --> 35:53.479
Go after Peter.

35:53.510 --> 35:55.774
Go after him?
Yes, for racial disparities

35:55.820 --> 35:58.789
when he was SA. I gave the
new speech to the teleprompter.

35:58.820 --> 36:00.617
What changed?

36:00.650 --> 36:03.380
Nothing. I was wrong.
This is the smart thing to do.

36:03.420 --> 36:04.626
(applause and cheering
in distance)

36:04.660 --> 36:07.549
Oh, that's Prady.
He's doing well.

36:07.590 --> 36:09.524
Yeah. You're next.

36:09.560 --> 36:11.699
Go after Peter.
Kill him.

36:11.730 --> 36:14.563
No mercy.

36:14.600 --> 36:16.591
Okay.

36:18.910 --> 36:21.572
FIFE:
Oh-ho, yeah!

36:21.610 --> 36:26.400
Welcome to the Freedom Factory.
Just-Just signed the lease

36:26.450 --> 36:28.771
and got a copy
of the keys right here.

36:28.820 --> 36:31.641
We finally have all this,
this elbow room.

36:31.690 --> 36:33.544
And-and the... the heater works.

36:33.590 --> 36:36.559
I, I think about all the time
and money, uh, we wasted

36:36.590 --> 36:38.524
trying to print
in my parents' garage.

36:38.560 --> 36:40.778
Yeah, we're not gonna miss
that damn icebox.

36:40.830 --> 36:42.422
(taps key)

36:42.460 --> 36:44.599
(phone ringing)

36:47.470 --> 36:49.961
McVeigh.

36:50.000 --> 36:51.900
I'm sorry... what?

36:51.940 --> 36:53.999
Have you tried printing the gun

36:54.040 --> 36:55.803
in a cold-temperature
environment?

36:55.840 --> 36:56.909
Have I...?
(stammers)

36:56.940 --> 36:58.840
Who is this?
Kalinda.

36:58.880 --> 37:01.576
See, low or fluctuating
temperatures can impede

37:01.620 --> 37:04.487
the layers of plastic
from adhering correctly.

37:08.860 --> 37:09.451
(applause)

37:09.490 --> 37:10.752
Every politician struggles

37:10.790 --> 37:12.678
with the 11th Commandment.

37:12.730 --> 37:14.425
Speak no ill

37:14.460 --> 37:16.690
of your fellow party member.

37:16.730 --> 37:18.789
Because sometimes
you just disagree.

37:18.830 --> 37:21.799
But when that disagreement
is with someone

37:21.840 --> 37:24.468
who is not just
a fellow traveler, but...

37:24.510 --> 37:26.307
in my case, a spouse,

37:26.340 --> 37:28.706
it gets even more complicated.

37:28.740 --> 37:30.799
Because the most_ insidious
form of raCIsm

37:30.840 --> 37:32.774
is unconscious and exists
in our legal system.

37:32.810 --> 37:34.414
(line ringing)

37:34.450 --> 37:36.941
My husband was
a good state's attorney.

37:36.980 --> 37:38.948
But he made some mistakes.

37:38.990 --> 37:40.639
JOHNNY: Eli?
Consider yourself out of a job,

37:40.690 --> 37:41.884
you son of a bitch.

37:41.920 --> 37:44.059
Well, you do
what you have to do, Eli.

37:44.090 --> 37:46.479
I'm running a campaign.
It's already done.

37:46.530 --> 37:48.293
Enjoy the speech.

37:48.330 --> 37:51.493
ALICIA: There's the saying
"Racism without racist."

37:51.530 --> 37:54.966
I think this perfectly
describes Cook County

37:55.000 --> 37:56.934
and the SA's Office.

37:56.970 --> 37:58.961
(applause)

38:05.380 --> 38:06.699
I think about all the time
and money, uh, we wasted

38:06.750 --> 38:07.876
trying to print
in my parents' garage.

38:07.910 --> 38:09.775
We're not gonna miss
that damn icebox.

38:09.820 --> 38:13.085
You knew that printing in cold
temperatures warps the plastic

38:13.120 --> 38:15.418
and weakens the structure
of the gun, didn't you?

38:15.460 --> 38:19.419
This... is a new field

38:19.460 --> 38:21.928
with a lot of variables...
A Simple yes or no, please.

38:21.960 --> 38:22.892
Yes.

38:22.930 --> 38:24.420
And did you offer any warning

38:24.470 --> 38:25.892
as to the effect
of cold temperatures

38:25.930 --> 38:27.466
on the printing process?

38:27.500 --> 38:29.889
No, no, but buyer
needs to beware.

38:33.110 --> 38:35.829
Five million.

38:37.140 --> 38:38.448
(clears throat)
Excuse me?

38:38.480 --> 38:39.902
You have to
drop the suit

38:39.950 --> 38:41.577
and sign this
nondisclosure agreement.

38:41.620 --> 38:42.939
Fife doesn't have
that kind of insurance.

38:42.980 --> 38:44.538
Where is the money
coming from?

38:44.590 --> 38:45.841
An interested party
has been following the case.

38:45.890 --> 38:47.118
The NRA?

38:47.150 --> 38:48.811
No, private individuals
who understand

38:48.860 --> 38:50.111
the importance
of this evolving issue,

38:50.160 --> 38:52.128
and would be willing
to underwrite Fife's defense.

38:52.160 --> 38:53.787
We have a right to know.

38:53.830 --> 38:55.058
No, actually, you don't.

38:55.100 --> 38:56.829
But you have the right

38:56.860 --> 38:59.420
to take it, Mr. Summerfeldt,
and drop this suit.

38:59.470 --> 39:01.995
Or you don't... and then

39:02.040 --> 39:03.996
my mysterious benefactor

39:04.040 --> 39:06.031
uses his bounty of treasure
to destroy you.

39:07.610 --> 39:09.430
So, what do you say,
Mr. Summerfeldt?

39:11.880 --> 39:13.848
CANNING:
Alicia?

39:13.880 --> 39:15.575
How are you today?
Good.

39:15.620 --> 39:17.872
Looks like you might be, too.
Yeah.

39:17.920 --> 39:19.945
Getting stronger.
Good.

39:19.990 --> 39:21.514
So, are you setting me up?

39:24.020 --> 39:27.057
Am I, am I,
am I setting you up?

39:27.090 --> 39:29.058
The 18 million
you wanted donated--

39:29.100 --> 39:31.022
is that a scheme
with David Lee?

39:31.060 --> 39:33.824
I really have...

39:33.870 --> 39:35.895
no idea what you're
talking about.

39:35.940 --> 39:37.532
You wanted
your stocks liquidated

39:37.570 --> 39:39.765
and given
to a Palestinian charity?

39:39.810 --> 39:41.732
I-I what...?
The donor's family.

39:41.780 --> 39:43.998
You wanted
18 million given to them.

39:44.040 --> 39:45.701
You wanted to do good.

39:45.750 --> 39:47.001
No, I didn't!
What do you mean,

39:47.050 --> 39:47.778
what do you mean
I want to do good?

39:47.810 --> 39:49.710
You don't remember
the conversation

39:49.750 --> 39:51.843
we had yesterday?
You gave me power of attorney.

39:51.890 --> 39:53.187
Alicia, what the hell?!
Where's my money?!

39:53.220 --> 39:55.154
Well, there were
some complications.

39:55.190 --> 39:56.589
That's why I'm here.

39:56.620 --> 39:57.882
Anesthesia plus
tremor meds.

39:57.920 --> 40:00.718
I was in a, in a, in a,
in a fugue state!

40:00.760 --> 40:02.819
I can't... Where, where,
where's my money?!

40:04.500 --> 40:05.922
Right where it belongs.

40:05.970 --> 40:07.562
With David Lee.

40:07.600 --> 40:09.158
Oh, thank God!
Hmm.

40:09.200 --> 40:10.690
Okay.

40:10.740 --> 40:12.708
I'm going now.

40:12.740 --> 40:14.708
This was... great.

40:14.740 --> 40:16.469
Always fun talking to you.

40:16.510 --> 40:17.977
Alicia, wait!

40:18.010 --> 40:19.648
Can you, can you
hand me my phone?

40:23.150 --> 40:26.540
You mean... this phone here?

40:26.590 --> 40:27.989
Yeah, you know,
don't-don't kid around.

40:28.020 --> 40:29.055
Just hand me the phone.

40:29.090 --> 40:30.489
No.

40:30.520 --> 40:32.488
I think it looks good

40:32.530 --> 40:33.929
right...

40:33.960 --> 40:35.928
there.

40:35.960 --> 40:37.928
Alicia...
Good seeing you, Mr. Canning.

40:37.960 --> 40:39.564
(phone ringing)
Oh, now it's ringing!

40:39.600 --> 40:41.124
Can you get...? What...?

40:41.170 --> 40:42.660
Nurse!

40:54.150 --> 40:56.209
Just came to see
how you were domg.

40:56.250 --> 40:59.617
I'll be fine.

40:59.650 --> 41:02.949
But I think I owe
you an apology.

41:02.990 --> 41:05.720
I let my political passions

41:05.760 --> 41:08.058
drive a wedge between us.

41:08.090 --> 41:11.196
And that's never
been how we do things.

41:13.730 --> 41:15.095
True.

41:16.870 --> 41:20.135
Oh, he of few words.

41:29.050 --> 41:31.075
I think we need
to go away together.

41:31.120 --> 41:33.748
Good.

41:33.790 --> 41:36.884
What do you think about
a week in Italy this May?

41:36.920 --> 41:38.922
The Amalfi Coast.

41:38.960 --> 41:42.691
Actually, I was, uh,
thinking more like tomorrow.

41:42.730 --> 41:46.518
I can't get away for a week.

41:46.570 --> 41:48.697
Yeah, I know.

41:48.740 --> 41:52.107
Three days
of deer hunting in Wyoming

41:52.140 --> 41:54.574
with the richest men
in the country.

41:59.650 --> 42:02.073
Sure, let's go.

